text:
after you have identified those who have wounded you, the next step to your healing is forgiving them. this is not because they aren't wrong for wounding you, it's simply releasing them from your heart. when genuinely done, this act removes resentment, bitterness and anger and invites god's healing virtues to occupy your wounded soul.

text:
from one mom to all of you mamas out there: 
after my babies were born, there were appointments.

to check their latch.

to check their weight.

to check their hearing. 
to check the colour of their skin for signs of jaundice.

there were appointments.

there were regular pokes and prods.

their well-being was front and centre. 
i'd say, when it comes to our health-care system, they were well taken care of.

then there was me.

a first-time mom without a clue. 
engorged, bleeding, and stitched up.

sent home with some painkillers and stool softeners.

thrown into motherhood with the expectation my instincts would kick in.

that i would know how to handle colic and late night feedings.

that breastfeeding would come as nature intended. 
that my husband would sense my spiral into depression.

that i would know how to live in my new and very foreign body. 
that this stomach wouldn't make me feel hideous.

and my mind wouldn't make me feel less than they deserved.

no one poked me.

no one prodded.

no one checked my stitches, my healing, or my sanity until eight weeks postpartum.

and even then, it was a pat on the back and i was sent on my way.

our world forgets about mothers.

we slip through the cracks.

we become background noise.

and in that, we learn our role... our place in our family unit... to always come last.

folks, we can't put mothers last.

our babies need us. 
to be healthy.

to know that we are worthy.

to know that motherhood, while natural, can sometimes feel like the least natural role in our life.

and that deserves attention. 
mothers deserve attention.

we need our world to fuss over us the way they fuss over ten fresh fingers and ten fresh toes.

we need to be seen.

we need to be heard.

we need someone to not only ask if we're okay but to check time and time again, just to be sure. 
we're not just a uterus.

we're not just a lifeline to a new and precious soul. 
we're mothers.

and we need someone to make sure we're ok, too. (anonymous)
name: findSisterhood App

text:
*review*
.
yes! yes! yes! this was the kind of book about hades and persephone that i really wanted to read! this was everything i desperately craved for and even more. but most of all: this were hades and persephone as i really imagined them, based on the original greek myths. the personalities of all the gods were spot on and very well done. and i might have enjoyed zeus being called out quite a bit too much.

let me start with writing down that this is not really a retelling. as in, this is not a modern au or some other twist on the myths that have been passed down for generations. this is actually for the most part the myth as we know, but with some slight touches that fit the modern need of women like me, and with some other mythologies, especially troy, tied into it. but, the language of the book feels a little old fashioned at times, a little much tell and not always show and very flowery. after a while i got used to it and i find it very fitting, but it's not the easy to read ya you might expect.

i however really enjoyed reading this book so much. this is partly because the two perspectives, hades and persephone, are both very insightful. we really get to know them both, in all their glory and with all their flaws and strengths. and we get to witness them falling for each other and them making each others lives and worlds better.

but, we most of all experience how persephone blossoms into an independent woman, taking charge and learning that her suggestions are important, that she can make a difference and that she can really help those who need her most.

at the end of the book i realised that i've been reading a story about female empowerment and calling out the male pigs that prevented us from pursuing it.
.
.
#hadesandpersephone #erinkinsella #hades #persephone #greekmythology #feminism #metoo #femaleempowerment #bookish #bookworm #bookstagram #booklovers #reading #reader #bookdragon

text:
we're going to need more wine by gabrielle union is not your typical celebrity memoir. she begins the book by sharing that's she going to tell the stories she's only ever shared with her closest girlfriends. i rolled my eyes at this, thinking that's what everyone says.  i was very wrong. â€¢

union, who is called nicki by friends and family, shares it all in this book.  she writes candidly about her failed marriage,  being famous, being raped at gunpoint,  colorism, her prenup with her current husband basketball superstar dwyane wade, their struggle with infertility and what it's like raising black teenagers.  i'm not even sure i share this much personal stuff with my closest girlfriends. â€¢

i watched the oprah interview, after i finished the book.  it's really good too, have you watched it? â€¢

text:
heartfelt congrats to #bgbactor, @mandolinkelly, for running to be a democratic delegate in assembly district 51!! this is what using your voice looks likeâ€¼ï¸ and while everyone might fight for their mission in different ways, choosing to fight is what is important. congratulations madeline on making the bold decision to stand in your power and fight for something you believe in.
____
madeline's statement: "i believe that we can create a regenerative economy in california, and forge a green new deal that improves our community and elevates our state. i stand for healthcare for all, affordable housing, debt free college, and living wages. i want to listen to your ideas and spread them. we have untapped strength in our diversity and more voices need to be listened to and upheld. together, we can create real opportunities that cross barriers of identity and economic status.
____ 
after two years of organizing in the community, i have been on the front lines of social advocacy in los angeles. as an organizer for public banking (measure b) the sunrise movement, divest la, and #metoo, i am deeply connected to the grassroots call for change from our representatives and party leadership. i have marched alongside you, and gone to our representatives to change policy on behalf of the people. i will bring a progressive, solution-focused conversation to our california democratic party. it is not enough to have good ideas, but we need leadership that fosters bravery in these times, and we must put forward solutions to create a better tomorrow, for our people and our planet. i will listen to you, and fight for what matters to you, so that our party will better represent the long term interests of the people over the short term interests of the few. i am proud to be a part of the working progressives for ad 51 slate, alongside many other long term community members and advocates."

i strongly believe, such events should be organised on a regular bases, as it gives women from all classes to come on the same platform and learn how to be what they #deserve to be - #gorgeous inside out!

text:
â€œnothing in life so isolates us from healthy human relationships and from a relationship with god as does sexual abuse. any experience of sexual abuse - but especially child sexual abuse - violates our boundaries and our trust.â€
-shelter from the storm

it was a very rough week following my first blog post. i wrote through tears and all week the tears just kept coming. not in a hopeless way, more of a thawing and releasing. the experience of my adopted father, don, choking me unconscious was frozen in time, locked deep-freeze within me.

you can retell and think about all the stories with no problem. itâ€™s feeling about them - the lack of feeling about them that gets you stopped up. i was happy to not feel about them. i believed, â€œfrozen is goodâ€, but how many of us know what frostbite looks like? what does it feel like? how does it taste? 
iâ€™m unpacking the frozen parts, to thaw and slack off their ice so they can heal. you can join me www.teresabruce.blog this weekâ€™s blog title is, the big thaw. #metoo #timesup #sexualabusesurvivorsstories #assaultsurvivor #childabuse #abuse #inspirational #christianblogger #hope

text:
my sweet loves getting much needed rest by the fire. thereâ€™s nothing better than seeing them safe, cozy and content in my home. for many years that was not the case. we walked on eggshells, didnâ€™t feel safe, and never truly felt at ease. so this picture holds so much more meaning than what meets the eye. that i made it out. that i created a life for the 3 of us that is based on love, trust and unconditional love. no more fear. no more walking on eggshells. no more enduring rages that took their innocence and my self esteem. no more put downs. no more waiting for the other shoe to drop. no more hiding who we are and what we think to appease someone who just wanted control. no more fear of losing my children to made up accusations. no more court that caused so much anxiety, i couldnâ€™t sleep, eat or breathe. in 2014 my babies were stolen from me with a slew of lies and fabrications. it almost killed me. that kind of fear, loss and having no control changes a person. though justice prevailed the fear didnâ€™t end. itâ€™s taken years of hard work, grueling work to get here. and iâ€™m not the same person in so many good ways but also ways that have left me having a hard time trusting life; trusting people; trusting the process; trusting the universe to right the wrongs. iâ€™m still working on that. 
itâ€™s solely on me now physically, financially, and emotionally to protect them, nurture them, provide for them. it shouldnâ€™t be that a parent can decide that to continue to punish me, by bowing out of responsibilities that hurt the children. but thatâ€™s our reality. because of this iâ€™ve struggled, hard. iâ€™ve struggled to see through the anger. iâ€™ve struggled to understand. iâ€™ve struggled trying to let go of so much anger, too much anger that it was detrimental to my health, my heart and my belief in humanity. anger ruled my head and my heart for too long. creating questions i couldnâ€™t find answers to. why? what kind of parent does this? why do they get away with it? why does our system have really no way to right this wrong? how can someone be this angry and cruel? how do they live with themselves? 
i still donâ€™t have answers to the millions of questions (cont in comments)

at 15, i attended a gems outreach group, while in a secure detention facility. i disclosed to the gems outreach coordinator and family court advocacy coordinator (fcac) a history of commercial sexual exploitation and pimp control, dating back to 12. i worked with the fcac individually, and after engaging in services for a year, i gave a presentation to my fellow residents. i was the only resident in the history of my detention facility to reach the highest level of behavior. i mentored my fellow residents, explaining that innovation was rooted in believing in my own potential.
.

text:
not far from the #nanterre #faculty @uparisnanterre and beyond a #circus. after the large wooden door surmounted by a bronze bell, la @la_ferme_du_bonheur welcomes you across ornamental gardens, an #orchard, a vegetable garden of aromatic and medicinal, a horticultural #greenhouse, the whole in the center of @diocesenanterre.
before it was a raw yard, of 2500sqm, vestige of an old school from 1904, demolished in 1992, where stands now the "#favelatheater," a  self-built structure, very rustic, with second hand materials, completely transparent; hosting a convertible theater, dining room, dancefloor, steam room... where the family "is the pig" in winter. 
near to the ballroom, including the restaurant, with vintage furniture; completed by workshops construction costumes and scenery... all between the pigeon, the barn, the piggery, the backyard, the aviary, the career of horses... because before turning to a cultural project, la #fermedubonheur is a #farm, within at the origin, roger des prÃ©s, a former actor of the so-called "alternative rock" #1980s scene, staged shows that agrees to say "#theater", even if materials are not always texts, still today like: #dostoyevsky, outdoor #jeangiono stories with a herd of #sheeps in #transhumance, written policies or test radio of #jeangenet, #waltwhitman poetry...
in 1999, the @ministerecc has established a agreement with the ferme du bonheur, still in progress today... people celebrate their wedding in an amazing, political and poetic ritual. concretely, from the early hours of the creation of the farm, roger chose not to be the only one to create; thus, proposing to other artists, companies to distribute their works: theater, dance, scholarly and popular music, also film, visual arts... to mention a few: sophie lecarpentier, #jeannebalibar, alexis forest, jacques rebotier...

â€œwithout fanfare or even notice, the department of justiceâ€™s office on violence against women made significant changes to its definition of domestic violence in april. the obama-era definition was expansive, vetted by experts including the national center for victims of crime and the national domestic violence hotline. the trump administrationâ€™s definition is substantially more limited and less informed, effectively denying the experiences of victims of abuse by attempting to cast domestic violence as an exclusively criminal concern.
.
.
.
the previous definition included critical components of the phenomenon that experts recognize as domestic abuseâ€”a pattern of deliberate behavior, the dynamics of power and control, and behaviors that encompass physical or sexual violence as well as forms of emotional, economic, or psychological abuse. but in the trump justice department, only harms that constitute a felony or misdemeanor crime may be called domestic violence. so, for example, a woman whose partner isolates her from her family and friends, monitors her every move, belittles and berates her, or denies her access to money to support herself and her children is not a victim of domestic violence in the eyes of trumpâ€™s department of justice. this makes no sense for an office charged with funding and implementing solutions to the problem of domestic violence rather than merely prosecuting individual abusers.
.
.
.
for varied reasons, many survivors make an informed choice to not initiate a criminal case.
.
.
.
restoring nonphysical violence to the definition of domestic violence is critical. as the centers for disease control and prevention reports, over one-third of u.s. women (43.5 million) have experienced â€œpsychological aggressionâ€ at the hands of an intimate partner. experts have long recognized that the manipulative behaviors identified in the obama-era definition as restricting a victimâ€™s liberty or freedom can cause greater and more lasting damage than physical harm.â€
.
.
.

text:
his demeanor changed. once i heard his belt buckle hit the floor, he started to move with panic. i could feel him breathing really hard on my neck. and no matter how hard i fought and resisted, he got my pants down to my ankles. and before i could even take another breath, he was inside of me.

as i wrote that, my stomach turned. i love to write but there will never be a set of words that could ever describe what it's like to have somethingâ€¦ someone inside of youâ€¦ without your personal invitation.

i honestly don't remember how i got away. it was just 5â€¦ maybe 10 seconds of my body being invaded but 5-10 way too many.

but like i always do, i wiped my tearsâ€¦ fixed my clothesâ€¦ and walked out like i was fine before asking my friend if we could leave.
and immediately i felt... guilty.
//
this is just a small snippet of my new blogpost the belt buckle. this is my #metoo story but by the grace of god i was also able to tell 66 other stories from so many beautiful women (and a few brave men). follow the link in my bio for the full story! i hope whoever needs healing receives this. i hope the misguided receive this. i hope you receive it. â¤ï¸
name: Sierra Brown - Wellness Coach

but like i always do, i wiped my tearsâ€¦ fixed my clothesâ€¦ and walked out like i was fine before asking my friend if we could leave.
and immediately i felt... guilty.
//

text: blast from the past - band was called filthy dukes and the song is this rhythm. this must be at least 12 years ago by now, maybe even longer, and the band was at the time very underground cool. my longest working collab director, the great @sarahjchatfield directed this (when there werenâ€™t that many female directors around). if iâ€™m not mistaken, this was shot on 35mm and with old lomo anamorphic lenses. might have been my own set that i had purchased (but sadly no longer own). not sure. in any case, the clip is rather grainy and i remember we pushed the exposures pretty daringly. itâ€™s a dark piece, both literally and conceptually. i used to favor fuji stock at the time (it was more budget friendly than kodak), so thereâ€™s a high risk this was shot on that. if i were to guess, iâ€™d say their low contrast 400t stock, most likely. it was a favorite at the time. sadly, which i regret a lot, is i have no notes on equipment or stocks for my earlier work, so itâ€™s all guesswork. even more sad is that all videos then were telecined and colored in sd, so there will never be hd version of these older videos. too costly (and sometimes even impossible) to go back to locate the negatives and do a hd transfer and conform again. itâ€™s extra sad, because at the time hd was already a thing, but the record companies had no foresight and no desire to pay for the slightly more expensive hd transfers. i bet they regret that today with youtube and all the social media.... anyway, back to video - it was shot in some old school outside of london, all in a day. the actress, gia, had a great face that photographed well. i remember we ran out of time on last set, which was elaborate in sarahâ€™s mind, so had to rush through it in both the build and shooting of it. good times. @gialazarova #filthydukes #fuji400t #lomo #lomoanamorphic #arri #arri435 #sd #musicvideo #metoo #femaledirector #telecine

text:
i told him everything about me. he didn't run. i told him about my deepest darkest secrets. he wasn't frightened. i told him that i didn't need someone to save me. he stood by my side. 
there was a part of me that was scared as hell and the other that said it's time. i shared my story knowing that for some it may be too much and for others it was exactly what they needed to know that they are not alone. 
and as i cried he held me tightly. he's my silent samurai.

i remember a nice winter
all there was was snow
i sled around the neighborhood 
knowing exactly where to go..
i know what i was feeling
the thrill of letting go
my vision clearly 
on the road..
i was drawn like a magnet 
to the universal flow
the rhythm of surrender grabbed my attention 
it carried me on..
i felt like i was on a journey 
specially designed for me
knowing no one would ever live
exactly like me..
i gave myself over 
all there was was snow
it turned out to be an adventurous ride
leading me home..
i know what i was feeling 
the experience alone
held all sorts of meaning 
waiting to be explored..
i remember a nice winter
all there was was snow
since then everything changed..
..not so much
still sledding around the neighborhood 
with soul

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
the only way to stay at the bottom is if you hold on to some weights.
if you jest let go of the weights, you are being brought to surface for a breath of fresh air without having to do anything. 
just simply decide to let go of the weights. .
i literally experienced this and i realized its a good metaphor for life. 
if i just know what are the weights i need to let go... thoughts, people, situations.. you know... the same as you.. .
.
question for today: what weights are keeping me (you) at the bottom? 
a breath of fresh air, please? .

#selfcare #mindset #mentalhealth 
#use #your #brain #for a #change

text:
but every writer, renowned or self-proclaimed, stops to think whether this silsila (chain) of endless pain would end if they stopped writing. it doesn't. it won't.
those people then spit venom through their spoken words.
i know because i am that person
___________

the roots of this poem is in the stories that unfolded during the #metoo movement. i didn't speak much then because i was just dumbfounded, at a loss of words because many of the predators were men i held in high regard. i did not doubt the stories of those women but i could not believe these men could have done such a horrible thing, including men who called themselves feminists. slowly as i read people and their views i could finally believe that yes! writers could be very wrong in reality and farrr from whom we think them to be! just because they've a gift of weaving words beautifully does not make them a righteous person. they could be anything and we won't know. this realisation also applies to me. many a times people take me to be a very good person though i'm like everyone - flawed.

itâ€™s been over one year since the #metoo - idea established in the context of the accusations against harvey weinstein in oktober 2017. 
us-american actress alyssa milano started the movement through asking #women to rise up and talk open about their experiences with sexual harassment, discrimination and abuse.
the hashtag developed in one year into a globally known movement that deals with #equality of man and women. 
as a result many victims finally talked openly about their experiences and especially cases of people of the public have been disclosed such as george w. bush or kevin spacey. both were accused of abusing their authority to harass several women.
â€”
even though the hashtag has triggered a huge sensation, on personal level and in developing countries where access to the internet is only limited and where the inequality of women and men is way more profound this movement couldnâ€™t achieve anything.
â€”
itâ€™s still a long way to go till change reaches a global level, but we wonâ€™t give up.
â€”
to what extend is it ok for men to approach women? what do you think?

text:
d.l. hughley gets a lot of things right but he is severely wrong on terry crews' sexual assault. 
to question someone's manhood because they chose to restrain themselves and calmly but firmly check the agent who violated him is exactly why men have kept silent for so long when they suffer the indignities of sexual assaults.
there are situations where you could possibly deck someone and be done with it but crews was not in a situation where he could do that.
crews is brave for speaking out; perpetuating the stigma is why so many violators continue to get away with it.
d.l. should know better.
victims/survivors tell your stories. there is no shame in speaking out.

text:
in april, changes were made to the definitions of domestic violence and sexual assault appearing on the website of the department of justiceâ€™s office of violence against women.

these changes represent a shift to a more narrow definition of domestic violence and sexual assault, defining them through the criminal justice lens. however, the overwhelming majority of sexual assault and majority of domestic violence cases are not reported. and those that are reported rarely move forward to an arrest.

we are here for support 24/7: (516)542-0404

text:
this week on insight, i interviewed an incredibly brave human being. daniel goldberg is a survivor of sexual assault- and he decided to go public with his story on social media so that other people would not fall victim to his attacker. 1 in 6 men have experienced sexual assault, but shockingly around 90% of the people that responded to his story on facebook were women. most men chose to send private messages of solidarity. it is a problem that this issue is so taboo. the #metoo movement applies to men and women alike, and advocates like daniel need to continue taking a stand. @capdain 
if you want to watch this episode, please go to my facebook page @natasharktv.

text:
in japan, broken objects are often repaired with gold. the process is called kintsugi. instead of throwing away a broken piece or trying to hide it, they highlight it. the flaw is seen as a unique piece of the object's history, which adds to its beauty. think about this when you feel broken.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
our wounds in life are part of us. when we try to ignore or hide them, we are left in pieces. let us take time to tend to our broken pieces.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
with broken pieces from things we did that we regret, may we make any amends we can, may we make peace with our self, and may we accept this piece of our story.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
with broken pieces from wounds caused by life or others, may we do healing things such as share with friends, journal, pray, talk with a counselor, and practice self-care. through processing what happened and experiencing some healing, we are able to continue in life with these broken pieces. they are no longer something we try to keep hidden. we no longer see them only as markers of pain, but we also them telling the story of what we did with that pain. reminders that we are still here, and the pain didn't destroy us forever. reminders that we didn't let the wound have the last word. we fought for our self in the aftermath. â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
the mending, the streams of gold bringing all the broken parts together, tell the story of how we fought for our self, for our heart. they are beautiful symbols of the strength, perseverance, self-love, hope, and so much more we have demonstrated by embracing our broken pieces.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

text: listen here. you're gonna have setbacks, mistakes, hiccups, and off days while you're fine tuning your masterpiece. shoot... these eyes of mine keep giving me glaring red, itchy, inflamed and watery signs to open up and see things clearly. i'm back in my hometown and blessed to have family and friends that get me and let me poke and prod them for information to make sense of gaps i've had in my life because of cptsd and other related effects to traumas in my past. i'm honored that my mother will sit and listen to me reliving traumas she has been witness to and desparately helpless in at times. through my storytelling she is triggered, yet now has the tools i've shared with her to do her own healing. and so we heal together. you see those bumps in your road, those painful memories and tragedies your faced, if you were blessed with family and friends they also lived that pain for you in their own way. so this healing i hold space with isn't just for me, it's for the ones i love and love me even if they don't do anything but witness the unfolding of the healing for we are all connected. if you or your loved ones are going through or have been through something heavy ask me if there's anything i know of that can support you on your journey of healing i'mhappy to share. if i don't know i'll find someone that does. we're in this thing called life and love together. start there.

text:
men scared of women post #metoo need to be educated not cancelled
#
it might be satisfying to joke about cancelling all white men and how all men are trash, but it doesnâ€™t achieve anything (picture: ella byworth/metro.co.uk)according to the new york times, high powered men are avoiding working with young women because post #metoo, theyâ€™re scared. as a feminist, my initial instinct is we should solve this by putting all the rich white men on some kind of an island, like a leper colony for sexism. and according to the reaction online to the nyt article, iâ€™m not alone. but hereâ€™s the thing: i am never going to get my leper colony. it might be satisfying to joke about cancelling all white men and how all men are trash, but it doesnâ€™t achieve anything. rightly or wrongly (itâ€™s the latter) men are frightened of being accused of inappropriate behaviour by women. and while people like me can shout â€˜behave appropriately in the work place and everything will be fineâ€™ until weâ€™re blue in the face, itâ€™s not getting us anywhere. when it came out thatÂ mike pence never spends time alone with any woman who isnâ€™t his wife, we all rolled on the floor laughing. post #metoo, how many men are secretly followingâ€¦

text: i was worried this film might be unpleasant, enraging, or difficult to watch - and parts of it were, for sure - but it was also inspirational, empowering, and satisfying. untouchable, ursula macfarlaneâ€™s exploratory documentary about media mogul harvey weinsteinâ€™s rise, and fall, gives some history into miramax and what went on internally, but focuses primarily on genuine and heartfelt testimony from several of the women who came forward and were brave enough to say yes to being filmed - some of them you know of already, some you donâ€™t. this film honors them. the filmmakers very intentionally gave them the time and space to speak. their long pauses were unedited, heightening the emotional impact, and their faces often filled the whole screen, with them looking directly at the viewer. at times the silence was heavy in the theater, and we could hear them swallow or their lips part as we hung on their next word. this intensity was softened by beautiful geographic aerial photography - seemingly there to give us a break, i felt. during the q&a following (thank you, @ursulapics - everyone with a film at sundance should take the time to come to slc!) there was a standing ovation, and some of my takeaway (besides the fact that rosanna arquette is my new role model) is that #metoo cannot just be that thing that went viral in 2017. it was originally created in 2006. it must go on. we must have open dialogues. with each other. with men. with coworkers. with our sons. solidarity, truth, and working together is the way to let truth win over power. #untouchable #metoo #sundance2019 #womeninfilm

text:
in light of the super bowl activities occurring this week, we are dedicating our week to child sex trafficking prevention and awareness. if you are in or around the metro atlanta region, we need you to be on the lookout for possible child sex trafficking victims. this includes in and around local hotels and motels, as well as truck stops and residential neighborhoods. did you know that truck stops are prime locations for sex trafficking? they not only serve as the "business location" for traffickers, but they are also the transfer point for victims to be moved from one state or country to another. also, residential properties are in heavy rotation as well because they draw less attention than hotels and motels. so be on the lookout for random cars pulling up with underage kids. also, take note of an increase in random visitors entering a home in your neighborhood.rental services such as air bnb make it easier for traffickers to set up shop without being detected. and, while sex trafficking in atlanta isn't a new issue, there will be an increase in activity this week since there will be an onslaught of visitors in the area for the super bowl festivities. please keep your eyes open!! if you are a victim or suspect that a child may be a victim of human trafficking, please call 911 or call the national human trafficking resource center at 1-888-373-7888 for help. all victims of slavery and human trafficking have rights and are protected by international, federal, and state law. 
the hotline is:â€¨(1) anonymous and confidential;â€¨(2) available 24 hours a day, seven days a week;â€¨(3) able to provide help, referral to services, training, and general information; (4) accessible in 170 languages;â€¨(5) operated by a nonprofit, nongovernmental organization; andâ€¨(6) toll free. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist  #super bowl ğŸ“¸: @consultingexp fb page

text:
tarana burke. if you don't recognize her name or face, you will know her by her work. @taranajaneen is the founder of the #metoo movement. this badass women was named one of the "silence breakers" for how she broke the silence of sexual assault, sexual violence, and rape. of course, she couldn't have done it if thousands of men and women weren't willing to share their testimony of their past. this ground breaking movement opened america's eyes as to just how common this epidemic really is. 
if that wasn't enough, she also founded the just be inc. which helps promote wellness in young minority girls during the pivotal age between 12-18. she also had a large role in the #survivingrkelly docu-series. if you haven't watched that series, you should but it's a huge **trigger warning**
so thank you, tarana burke for being such a badass, and giving survivors, and young minority women a place where they can speak up, and feel safe! we need more people like her, now more than ever.

text:
feminism. is it necessary?
i'm @theexpater and i had this conversation with someone recently. they argued that feminism and especially the #metoo movement has become a trend, a fad, along with avo on toast and millennial unicorns.
seriously?!
sure, on the whole, feminism is now no longer a dirty word. amen to that.
sure, in parts of the world women enjoy much greater freedoms than their grandmothers could even dream of. 
but that's not to say we're there now.
most recently uae announced its equality awards, which were won by... wait for it... drum roll... men. all awards were won by men.
and what about the pay gap around the globe? in the us on average women earn 80% of a man's salary. 
for me at least, feminism may have shifted its focus, but it's as relevant and crucial as ever.

thank goodness for organisations like @aauwnational, @awidwomensrights
@timesupnow & @weareultraviolet 
what do you think? who are your feminist heroes?  #unitedinwomanhood
thank you ğŸ“· @arielebonte

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
close-up... see on the side of my face... yes.. i have a beard... the saloon guy told me have a threading done.. stupid fellow can shave his face but i have get a threading done and see hell in pain... i'm gonna keep the beard for now... not worth going through the pain.  getting rid of the upper lip moustache itself is painful enough. . 
fyi.. i have never got my eyebrows done.. i don't get the point...
i mean they are there for what joy? does anyone know the functions of eye brows? 
are they just an asset to be perfectly shaped? i don't know... doubts of the day... #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #metooÂ  #loneliness #pain #despair #prettygirls #perfectbody #hurtquotes #goodenough #positivevibes

text:
holding on! 
i am holding on to my blanket... i am suffering from severe pms as i am due and over an above i ate something stupid and landed with a stomach upset. .
the flash is on because i am in my room in the dark.. i am not confident enough to put on a face with no smile. a swollen,  kajal smudged face is what i have right now with messy hair.. the tear drops fall on my phone making it so hard to type as the letters go ffffdff and i have to wipe it with my shirt every 30 secs to get the tears off.
i had therapy today and i was alright...
the downfall was pretty rapid.... this is the life of a bipolar! 
worse being a girl whose menses cycles are in tact... #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #metooÂ  #loneliness #pain #despair #prettygirls #perfectbody #hurtquotes #goodenough #positivevibes

text: so i guess this is part of my problem. i am anxious, upset and frozen for 2 days where i lay in bed and do the bare minimum of work i have to do to keep up with clients. then he comes back picks a fight to try and justify why he left. there is travel for work so we leave town and he acts like nothing happens but of course some shady moments while we are away. if you could only imagine what is said and why all this is happening. i know deep in my heart this is not my fault. i know that when someone shames you and says this is all your fault and this is happening because you are fat cannot be true. maybe true for him. if you saw me walking down the street you wouldnâ€™t notice me. i donâ€™t stand out as skinny or fat or anything. am i and athlete shape, no! could i lose another 20 to 30 lbs yes i can and itâ€™s been a constant struggle my whole life. but i exercise regularly and my biggest challenge in life is to eat properly and take care of myself. i started this post about 3 weeks ago but have been so busy working i never finished. it does say something about consistency and something i struggle with but work has been so much it was all i could handle. #metoo #codependency #recovery #ithastogetbetter #workhard #mentalhealth #secrets #lies

text:
as lilia tarawa describes her life in a cult, i found it so eerily familiar.  i realize the techniques that her grandfather (the leader of the cult) and her community used to brainwash and break her down were the same the same as my ex mother in law and her family.

1. shame and humiliate you in front of others. she would tell me i'm too fat, too outspoken, etc.

2. use the community to reinforce this belief that you're the problem. my ex husband's identical twin (paul tsai) and her husband, din tsai, have said her beating me is justified because i'm the problem.

3. make you believe that you're unworthy of love. she would ask me regularly what i did for her son. then she would praise her sons in front of me and tell me how lucky i am to be with her son.

today, like lilia tarawa, i break the chains of this abuse because of my love for my son.

it wasn't until i watched this video (https://tinyurl.com/ydymh57w) that i realize that i couldn't write my book 3 years ago because i hadn't learned the greatest lesson yet - self love.

and that is why i'm so proud to finally come to a title that fully encompasses my journey, "belonging: self love lessons from a workaholic depressed insomniac lawyer." if you have been in an abusive relation - emotional, verbal, or physical - know that you are worthy of love.

leaving may be difficult.  but happiness is possible.

#selflove #speakupshoutout #womenmatter #metoo

we are infinitely happy to have yuko shimizu @yukoart as our next lw&d interview.  originally from tokyo and now based in new york, yuko is a freelance illustrator and instructor at the school of visual arts. illustration is actually yukoâ€™s second career. she says, â€œi have an undergraduate degree in business (advertising and marketing), and had a corporate pr career in japan for 11 years before i quit, moved to ny, and enrolled myself in sva to start a new career pathâ€¦ i always loved to draw, and getting a stable corporate job never made me happy.Â around the age of 30, i stopped and thought about whether it was really something i wanted to keep doing. the answer was no. so from there, i went soul searching, then made up my mind to try myself out in art. worked a few years more to save up enough money to move to ny and pay for four years of art schoolâ€¦ and here i am!â€ her advice to other creatives: â€œi canâ€™t speak for other industries, but as a freelance illustrator mainly working in editorial, book and ad markets, i canâ€™t stress enough: none of my clients ever care if you are a woman, or a man, young or old, an american or not, minority or not, if you have phd or dropped out of high schoolâ€¦ you are only judged by the images you create, and that is really really liberating and a fantastic field to be working in.â€ yuko shimizuâ€™s full interview is on our lw&d website listed in our profile above. #ladieswinedesign #yukoshimizu âœ¨ğŸ™ŒğŸ’¥
.
.
.

text:
hello everyone,
angela christofilou (@angela_photographs / @protests_photos) here taking over insta for this week. 
i've been building an archive of protest photography for the past few years so i'll be mainly posting various images from these for this take-over.
the image in the intro poster was taken during a @sistersuncut march in nov 2015. trafalgar square's fountains were dyed red to resemble the blood of women killed by domestic violence. "they cut, we bleed"
in this post, i have featured a photo i shot at the women's march in london. 
thanks to @photo_scratch for having me and for your time.
#womensmarch #london #sistersuncut #metoo #documentaryphotography #photojournalism #portrait #protest #photoscratch #angelachristofilou #londonphotocommunity #photonetwork #blackandwhite #streetphotography #shotoncanon

text:
i wrote â€œgirls suckâ€ in sharpie on my high school deck â€˜cause i was confused about my gender and frustrated at how to fit in with the presented â€œoptionsâ€ for how girls / women â€œshould beâ€ required such disempowerment and sameness ... it just didnâ€™t work for me at all #90s #riotgrrrl #feminist
.
i also had deep unconscious fear of women / women in authority positions due to emotional & psychological abuse #gaslighting from my mother #cptsd and inappropriate touch from a gymnastics coach before the 5th grade
.
becoming â€œone of the boysâ€ helped me hide from my own cis-gender identity crisis by adopting the behaviors and dress of the #punk and #skater boys i hung around and felt the most comfortable with
.
â€œif iâ€™m one of the boys, then i will be safe from sexual assault / being harassedâ€
.
or, so i thought ... despite wearing clothes that mostly hid my body & staying skinny (underdeveloped) as a three sport athlete, i still got my crotch & barely there breasts grabbed at punk shows crowd-surfing & in mosh pits
.
later in life, that â€œone of the boysâ€ false protection mechanism took the form of being overly logical / analytical in the workplace & denying my feelings, drinking â€œwith the guysâ€ shot-for-shot at happy hours, and building my body into a muscled, more â€œmasculineâ€ shape via #crossfit for 7 years
.
thereâ€™s so much more to unpack here & write about ... just sharing a bit now as in real-time i am feeling such gratitude for the healing work iâ€™ve done to define, create & embody my own sense of #gender #sexuality #female #feminine w empowered, grounded, mystical, rich earth-mother #empress #divinefeminine energy vs. market #stereotypes
.
and i am proud of the progress iâ€™ve made in healing my relationship to my mother, and from the sexual assault of my younger years & being raped a few years ago #metoo #timesup
.
it is wonderful to feel safe in my own skin, and to love all of it, curves and all without fear ... to know my power comes from within and doesnâ€™t have a damn thing to do with what i wear, how i ride, or what anyone else thinks about how i â€œpresentâ€ my gender or sexuality
.
the body is merely a #meatsuit for the soulâ€™s expression anyway ... conâ€™t ğŸ‘‡ğŸ¼

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: â€œwe exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.â€ documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takersâ€™ facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebookâ€™s â€œplatform policyâ€ allowed only collection of friendsâ€™ data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebookâ€™s role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate â€œinformation warfareâ€ against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

.

 survivors are often asked what they were wearing, what they did toÂ â€œencourageâ€ the perpetrator, or even why they didnâ€™t fight back more.

with the #metoo movement, victim-blaming remains aÂ tenacious problem.

the tendency to blame the victim may be part of society's conditioning. .

ask yourself would any woman intentionally put themselves in a position to be abused?

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
hurt a poet and sheâ€™ll make you her poetry.
she wonâ€™t name you, worry not,
but youâ€™ll itch and write at the lament,
even if you claim youâ€™re made of diamonds.
.
leave a poet and sheâ€™ll see you in the skies,
musingly staring with the ghost of a smile,
thinking of all the words she could use
to embellish her next cathartic piece with.
.
make a poet cry and with every tear
that escapes her weary eyes,
sheâ€™ll create oceans with the currents so unfathomable
that your winds of oblivion will stir up.
.
so tear a poet apart and sheâ€™ll at once
write and write about you; exploit your evil.
come up with the most melancholic beauty
that youâ€™ll ever read when you find someone
just like yourself.
.
and isnâ€™t that what poets do best?
suffer pain like every other being,
only to write about it as if
writing is their salvation, and poetry, their sin.
.
.
sneha talwar.
(@issnehaaa)
.
.
.
.

text: funambulism: a poem from 10 years ago that was one of the influences of my recent painting by the same name. funambulism is the art of tightrope walking. i wrote this piece 10 years ago. itâ€™s crazy how much changes in that time. as i appreciate my lifeâ€™s ups and downs now, itâ€™s clear that my view was very different then. i tell people all the time that positivity is something that takes practice to become second nature and determination to see during the hard times. itâ€™s clear that i didnâ€™t have much practice at it ten years ago. that said, i love this time capsule, shows how much iâ€™ve learned and grown. the best part about this piece though is its structure. iâ€™m always playing with words but this small series was extra special in its complexity. this was part of my â€œfour poems on a pageâ€. the challenge i created for myself in these was creating four stanzas that could stand alone. so, if you read this poem across and line by line, you get one picture. if you read this piece by its independent columns (left, middle, right), you have an additional 3 unique expressions. i also love the visual balance of the words on the page. that was very intentional, wanted it to reflect a central body with things teetering on either side as iâ€™d imagine the experience of walking down a tightrope. it was a fun exercise that i might just revisit sometime. anyway, hereâ€™s another version of the 10 year challenge. #livingwithart #jennifire #tenyearchallenge #attitudeofgratitude #happinessishere #mondayvibes #balancedlife #mindfulness #poetry #whereicomefrom #metoo #writersofinstagram #simplelife  #womenartists #dallasart #glasslife #weareone #tightrope #oprahsbookclub #bigtop #balancingact #artlove  #womenwriters #meditation #plur #plurlife #blessup #soulshine #lovequotes #lifelesson

text:
"h e a r i n g"
definisi (noun): an opportunity to state your case and be heard.

namun, begitu sampai di ruangan dpr, terkuaklah sudah:
anggota dewan dprd yang hadirãƒ¼kecuali bu agathaãƒ¼jelas hadir tidak untuk mendengarkan.

mereka justru hadir untuk menyangkal,
mempertanyakan,
meragukan.
seolah-olah perempuan-perempuan yang rela menyisakan waktunyaãƒ¼yang rela jauh-jauh datang dari seluruh pelosok jawa timur, bahkan dari tubanãƒ¼ "ujug-ujug datang" tanpa mempelajari dahulu apa itu ruu penghapusan kekerasan seksual.

niat baik, katanya. ya, dengan mempertanyakan berulangkali apa yang padahal bersumber dari pengalaman hidup perempuan itu sehari-hari. 
ala-ala paternalistik, seolah dewan dprd mengetahui pengalaman hidup perempuan lebih baik daripada perempuan itu sendiri. (di sini saja kami 'lelah hayati', tidak bisa dibayangkan korban yang seusai melewati trauma, harus diinterogasi dengan pertanyaan senonoh berulang kali). apa yang terjadi di ruang dprd jawa timur ini sejatinya adalah refleksi dari bagaimana masyarakat memperlakukan penyintas kekerasan seksual: 
penyintas diragukan, 
disangkal, 
dibuat seolah "gila", dan 
dipersalahkan.

oh ya di sini lucunya: mereka meng-klaim jika pasal dari ruu ini ada yang digerogoti, ini seolah-olah karena kegagalan kita mengawal ruu ini, dan ketidakpahaman kita atas ruu ini. ini logik yang aneh. 
justru inilah tugas anda, dewan dprd, untuk mengawal ruu ini supaya ruh dan esensi dari ruu ini tidak diamputasi. anda tidak berpikir bahwa pajak kami digunakan untuk membayar anda duduk-duduk santai di ruang ber-ac, kan?

namanya saja "hearing": coba buka hati dan telinga, agar bukti-bukti, narasi, dan suara  kami tidak "masuk kuping kiri, keluar kuping kanan". ini bukan waktu bagi anda untuk bersikukuh berdasarkan apa yang menurut anda benar. justru, ini waktu untuk mengkritisi pengetahuan anda dengan pengalaman empiris perempuan yang sesungguhnya. 
anda beruntung.kapan lagi toh anda ada kesempatan untuk mendengarkan suara perempuan korban kekerasan yang selama ini dibungkam masyarakat? ã€16haktp jawa timurã€‘
ã€hearing dengan dprd jawa timur @ 17 dec 18ã€‘
ã€jaringan jawa timur pendukung pengesahan ruu penghapusan kekerasan seksualã€‘

text:
i wanted my first post to come directly from my heart, thus i share with you the heart gallery. my platform for mrs. florida usa 2019 is to represent children and women who are victims of domestic violence. our strong survivors of the cruelty in this world. there is no one perhaps more vulnerable to this cruelty than children.
â¤
a decade ago i stumbled upon the heart gallery which serves as an online platform to directly connect foster children with adoptive parents  in what they dream will be their forever home.
â¤
this shook me to the core. i was in tears, in fact, i am never not in tears viewing these galleries. to me, it is an unimaginable quest to be a child on this earth and long for nothing more than parents to love and protect you. i wish i could be a mother to each and every one of these dear children. these amazing, incredible, survivors.
â¤
my love for these child survivors catapulted me into my career as an attorney & child advocate. over this next year as mrs. florida usa i will represent these champions of hope and bring attention to their struggle with my voice. i hope that you will join me in my campaign to bring as much assistance and guidance to these amazing warriors as we can. to help prove to them that there are so many kind souls in this world that love and care for them. to assure them to hold on to their hope and follow their dreams! 
thank you for reading! â¤
very truly yours, 
krista lori thompson,  esq.

text:
** trigger alert** when i say you are worthy, don't settle for less, you are enough etc.... i'm not just throwing cute and fluffy words at you. i affirm your divinity because i know too well the dangers of a low self esteem. as a child i was sexually violated several times, i lost my mother at 9, bounced around from family to family and then from foster home to foster home. i was broken. i hated what i saw in the mirror and i went around searching for love and validation from all the wrong places. attracting relationships that mirrored the toxic beliefs that i had of myself. as a young adult i experienced domestic violence, cheated on and just accepted it as my reality. i gave birth to 4 children. i dpent 17 years with there father even though the relationship was falling apart. i stayed cause i knew if i left i would end up raising them on my on. i knew that i would end up being by myself because of fear that someone would do to them what was done to me. for years i went through life fearful and full of abandonment issues. somewhere along the way i started to heal. i walked away from people, situations and habit that wasn't serving me. i started to chose me....started to love me. it has been a long and at times a painful journey back to wholeness. but it's been worth it. i am worth it and so are you. in the spring i'll be 42, my oldest daughter will be 19, her sister 16 and i have 2 little boys. i thank god for grace. not only do i not look my age, i don't look like half the things i've been going through. that's why it's important for us to tell our testimony. because by god's grace most of us don't look like what we've been through.... grown through. 
romana

text:
have you tried unsuccessfully to heal your shame? discover how shame and control are intricately tied together; and that when you give up your attachment to control, you will find your shame disappearing.

many people on a healing path have found it extremely challenging to heal their shame. yet, when you understand the purpose of shame, you will be able to move beyond it.

shame is the feeling that there is something basically wrong with you. the feeling of guilt is about doing something wrong, whereas shame is about being wrong at the core. the feeling of shame comes from the belief that, â€œi am basically flawed, inadequate, wrong, bad, unimportant, undeserving or not good enough.â€ https://youwillbearwitness.com/2019/01/28/why-we-feel-shame-and-how-to-conquer-it/ #youwillbearwitness #emdr #erinfado #ptsd #peterfox #ptsdsurvivor #ptsdrecovery #ptsdawareness #stopracism #stopbullying #stopchildabuse #metoo #trauma #therapydog #dissociativeidentitydisorder

itâ€™s taken me days to post this. @womensmarch is such an emotionally charged day for me. i feel all the feels. 2017: i was 9 months pregnant, marching in disbelief at the inauguration of dumb fuck in charge, with my two best girl friends and a sea of sisters. we marched because we literally didnâ€™t know what else to do. we marched because we knew we had to do something. we marched before we knew the enormity and seriousness of what a trump presidency was really capable of. it was before #metoo and before #familiesbelongtogether and before #protectmueller. 2018: i marched with my baby earthside and my very best friend. we marched because we were mad. it was less organized, more angry. we marched and we couldnâ€™t believe we still needed too. we were a year in and #metoo allegations abounded. we marched because we had to. 2019: this year i marched with my toddler and husband. we missed dearly our @morgantaylorbradley . this year we marched to remind ourselves and the world that weâ€™re still here.  we may not know how to fix it, but weâ€™re here and we care. we marched for babies separated from their mamas, which seems like so many catastrophes ago. we marched for dr blasey ford, because #webelievewomen. we marched for transgendered people in the military. we marched for homeless solutions. the issues confronting our world just keep compounding. and it feels more and more helpless. but i have to remember that there is light in the dark. we #tookbackthehouse and we have young, vibrant, diverse and female representation! weâ€™ve got #speakerpelosi taking no prisoners and building no walls. we did that. 2020: iâ€™m sure weâ€™ll be marching again. hopefully with a roster of strong, progressive female voices running to replace this dumb fuck. whatever the cause or the campaign, weâ€™ll be there for it.

thereâ€™s a powerful energy and focus that supports us in our personal and collective endeavors when we watch & discuss videos like tarana burkeâ€™s tedtalk (founder of #metoo ). thanks for gathering us at the women of color content creators mashup, @byjessicanguyen of @projectvoicepod and @hausoftiffany of @spill_stories . ~
"the me too movement is a witch hunt." right? "me too is dismantling due process." or, "me too has created a gender war." the media has been consistent with headline after headline that frames this movement in ways that make it difficult to move our work forward, and right-wing pundits and other critics have these talking points that shift the focus away from survivors. so suddenly, a movement that was started to support all survivors of sexual violence is being talked about like it's a vindictive plot against men. 
but be clear: this is a movement about the one-in-four girls and the one-in-six boys who are sexually assaulted every year and carry those wounds into adulthood. it's about the 84 percent of trans women who will be sexually assaulted this year and the indigenous women who are three-and-a-half times more likely to be sexually assaulted than any other group. or people with disabilities, who are seven times more likely to be sexually abused. it's about the 60 percent of black girls like me who will be experiencing sexual violence before they turn 18, and the thousands and thousands of low-wage workers who are being sexually harassed right now on jobs that they can't afford to quit. 
this is a movement about the far-reaching power of empathyâ€¦trauma halts possibility. movement activates it.

so much of what we hear about the me too movement is about individual bad actors or depraved, isolated behavior, and it fails to recognize that anybody in a position of power comes with privilege, and it renders those without that power more vulnerable. we have to reeducate ourselves and our children to understand that power and privilege doesn't always have to destroy and take -- it can be used to serve and build.

text:
#bodydigging #golddigging #bodydigger (2 posts) #golddigger (218,088 posts) #doublestandards #metoo #feminism #hijab #mateselection #bodyobjectification #heterosexual #dating

why is it okay for a man to be a body digger, but it isn't okay for a woman to be a gold digger?

even though studies on mate selection, state that heterosexual men value women's bodies (their #beauty, #sexuality, and #fertility) most when selecting a mate -- they seem to have little self-awareness as to this fact. especially when the comparable practice for a woman value moat a man's resources and ability to protect, is severley put down.

it's unlikely that any one person's body or resources is going to satisfy everybody in the whole world. and it's likely that few people are going to like being valued for their body (women)  or resources (men) unless they are engaging in the exchange theory. people like sex workers, sugar daddies and sugar mamas, sugar babies and sugar boys are upfront about this exchange and i make no moral judgment. i think people should go after what they want. but what really irks me is the lack of understanding and awareness of men primarily valuing women's bodies and yet they denounce what women want.

oh yes, she should want him just for his body and maybe his personality. just never want him because he has wealth and status.

considering movies like the prince who pretends that he is a popper because he wants to make sure did the woman doesn't want him for his wealth and status. because who wants to be wanted for these superficial and shallow things? unless it is to benefit them.

and just like the movie shrek and the fat and ugly turning into a beautiful princess - people love the idea of being loved for the things that can't be seen too readily.

so unless you want to be fair about it, and you're okay with a woman taking advantage of your resources and your status - will you please take a moment to think about how your body digging affects women around the world?

it is unlikely that any one person's body or resources is going to satisfy everybody in the whole world. and it is likely that few people are going to like being valued for their body (women)  or resources (men) unless they are engaging in the exchange theory. people like sex workers, sugar daddies and sugar mamas, sugar babies and sugar boys are upfront about this exchange and i make no moral judgment. i think people should go after what they want. but what really irks me is the lack of understanding and awareness of men primarily valuing women's bodies and yet they denounce what women want.

oh yes, she should want him just for his body and maybe his personality. just never want him because he has wealth and status.

considering movies like the prince who pretends that he is a popper because he wants to make sure did the woman does not want him for his wealth and status. because who wants to be wanted for these superficial and shallow things? unless it is to benefit them.

and just like the movie shrek and the fat and ugly turning into a beautiful princess - people love the idea of being loved for the things that can not be seen too readily.

so unless you want to be fair about it, and you are okay with a woman taking advantage of your resources and your status - will you please take a moment to think about how your body digging affects women around the world?

text:
this is the face of ptsd. unedited, unfiltered, unable to be apologetic even if it wanted to. 
it has been a long time since something has triggered my negative thought patterns associated with ptsd, but tonight it hit me hard. the kicker is that it was a simple, every day conversation that set me off. i've been speaking of ptsd in the past tense for years and tonight made me realize it can never be past tense, it is and will always be the harbinger of fear at the back of my mind. 
i am a strong, independent, hard-working woman and because of this it is often assumed that i'm not susceptible to the same emotions other women feel. the reality is that i have been so scarred by my past that i've built a wall inside myself to hold all of these emotions at bay, and on the outside i am composed and logical. when the ptsd is triggered and the negative thought patterns take hold - i freeze. just like i did that day so many years ago. the thoughts revolve in a never ending cycle of bad to worse and i shut down. until i finally register: this is a symptom of my ptsd and i am creating these scenarios because of my fear of being hurt again. "i must not fear. fear is the mind killer. fear is the little-death that brings total obliteration. i will face my fear. i will permit it to pass over me and through me and when it has gone past, i will turn the inner eye to see it's path. where the fear has gone there will be nothing. only i will remain." dune, frank herbert. 
#ptsd #fear #dune #frankherbert #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #thisiswhatptsdlookslike #negativethoughts #cbt #stopthepattern #mantra #iamstronger #metoo

"i must not fear. fear is the mind killer. fear is the little-death that brings total obliteration. i will face my fear. i will permit it to pass over me and through me and when it has gone past, i will turn the inner eye to see it is path. where the fear has gone there will be nothing. only i will remain." dune, frank herbe.

text:
via @foxnashville: 
a survey by the violence policy venter says tennessee is 4th in the nation for men killing women in domestic-related homicides.

on saturday, one survivor walked through the streets with bruises all over her face to bring attention to the problem.

it's 2 p.m. in the gulch.

sparkle johnson and her kids are sitting on the bench, wondering if anybody will ask her if she's okay.
her face is covered in bruises after her husband's last attack. â€œthe cut of the scissors or from the dvd that he was slicing at me,â€ she said.

she then gets up to cross the street, and â€“ finally â€“ a man comes up to her. â€œeverything okay? you sure? what's up? what's your name, darling?â€ he asks.

he asks her how he can help. â€œmake sure you get the cops involved first,â€ he says, â€œbecause that's going to be the first place that's going to put him behind bars.
she tells him the bruises are fake, but the story is real â€“ a direct reenactment of how she looked after her last attack. â€œanything that could be done, was done, except for taking my life. i wasn't shot, but i was shot at. he forced me to play russian roulette and put the gun in my mouth. he beat me, he raped me, cut me,â€ johnson said.  she then walked through the crowd of people taking pictures with the famous wings; hundreds of people, and not a single question. â€œthey pointed, they whispered, but nobody offered to help me. even one lady, she stopped to let my son pet her dog but she didn't even acknowledge what was happening.â€
.
.
.

via @foxnashville: 
a survey by the violence policy venter says tennessee is 4th in the nation for men killing women in domestic-related homicides.

on saturday, one survivor walked through the streets with bruises all over her face to bring attention to the problem.

it is 2 p.m. in the gulch.

sparkle johnson and her kids are sitting on the bench, wondering if anybody will ask her if she's okay.
her face is covered in bruises after her husband's last attack. â€œthe cut of the scissors or from the dvd that he was slicing at me,â€ she said.

she then gets up to cross the street, and â€“ finally â€“ a man comes up to her. â€œeverything okay? you sure? what's up? what's your name, darling?â€ he asks.

he asks her how he can help. â€œmake sure you get the cops involved first,â€ he says, â€œbecause that's going to be the first place that's going to put him behind bars.
she tells him the bruises are fake, but the story is real â€“ a direct reenactment of how she looked after her last attack. â€œanything that could be done, was done, except for taking my life. i wasn't shot, but i was shot at. he forced me to play russian roulette and put the gun in my mouth. he beat me, he raped me, cut me,â€ johnson said.  she then walked through the crowd of people taking pictures with the famous wings; hundreds of people, and not a single question. â€œthey pointed, they whispered, but nobody offered to help me. even one lady, she stopped to let my son pet her dog but she didn't even acknowledge what was happening.â€
.
.
.

text:
getting treated poorly doesnâ€™t mean you are required to take the punches.
.
if you have a quiet demeanour, or if thereâ€™s something about you that others find threatening to their own self-worth, you will find your limits being tested. not because thereâ€™s anything wrong with you, but because you stand out.
.
some people will push and push to see how far you can go before you finally decide to stand your ground. thatâ€™s how bullies operate. they see something in you that they lack in themselves. it terrifies them. they probe your weaknessesâ€”and once they see an opening, they go in for the kill like a predator.
.
when your rights are being challenged, itâ€™s okay to speak up and let your voice be heard. but itâ€™s equally important to do it in a way that is non-destructive while still allowing you to preserve your respect, dignity, and class. no one is ever worth tarnishing your own character over.
.
when youâ€™re honest in your approach and stay calm, cool, and collected, you will be amazed at the amount of respect you earnâ€”especially from those who initially made you feel inferior. your actions end up speaking volumes about the kind of person you are and it makes others question the way they conduct themselves. and a tone that was once higher than yours loses its power.
.
who they are should never stop you from smiling. they should never stop you from being your best self. they should never stop you from treating other people right.
.
itâ€™s crucial to understand that how people choose to behave is a direct reflection of their own character, their own projections, their own insecurities. what they do or say has absolutely nothing to do with you and everything to do with them.
.
donâ€™t feel bad when someone treats you a certain way. donâ€™t carry blame inside of you. donâ€™t allow the pain they havenâ€™t confronted to become yours. leave that burden with its rightful owner. any form of abuse is not to be tolerated. if they attempt to disrupt your peace, you say what you need to say and walk away with your head held high. and if you need support, seek it.
.
when you own a situation and choose not to surrender to defeat, the control they mightâ€™ve thought they had is over.

text:
at least once a day i hear someone in my life use the phrase â€œi feel out of controlâ€ or â€œi avoided ____ because i feared being out of controlâ€. .
hereâ€™s is a little, well-known, secret though. our sense of control is never built in the big things. it is always built in the small things. .
take a moment today and narrate what your doing by adding in where you have control. .
in this moment, as i drive to work/school, i have control of what i listen to, how loud i play it, if i skip or not. i am in control of which direction i take, how quickly i drive, if i use my turn signals, or honk at another driver. .
itâ€™s amazing how something so mundane and at times thoughtless activity is a foundation to recognize our control, our power, in our lives.
.
.
.
. . .
